19|6|10|3}}\n|-\n|align=center|[[Bosnia and Herzegovina national football team|Bosnia and Herzegovina]]\n|align=center|\u2014\n|align=center|21 December 2019\n|align=center|Present\n{{WDL|0|0|0|0}}\n|-\n!colspan=4|Total\n{{WDLtot|1140|638|260|242}}\n|}\n\n==Honours==\n===Player===\n'''AEK Athens'''\n*[[Super League Greece|Alpha Ethniki]]: [[1977\u201378 Alpha Ethniki|1977\u201378]], [[1977\u201378 Alpha Ethniki|1978\u201379]] \n*[[Greek Football Cup|Greek Cup]]: [[1977\u201378 Greek Cup|1977\u201378]] \n\n===Individual===\n'''Awards'''\n*[[Croatian Footballer of the Year#List of winners|Yugoslav Footballer of the Year]]: 1972\n\n'''Performance'''\n*[[Yugoslav First League]] Top Goalscorer: [[1969\u201370 Yugoslav First League|1969\u201370]] (20 goals)\n*[[List of top goalscorers in Superleague Greece by season|Alpha Ethniki Top Goalscorer]]: [[1979\u201380 Alpha Ethniki|1979\u201380]] (25 goals)\n*[[Greek Football Cup|Greek Cup]] Top Goalscorer: [[1977\u201378 Alpha Ethniki|1977\u201378]], [[1978\u201379 Alpha Ethniki|1978\u201379]]\n*[[Brazil_Independence_Cup#Goalscorers|Brazil Independence Cup 1972 Top Goalscorer ]]\n\n===Manager===\n'''Vele\u017e Mostar'''\n*[[Yugoslav Cup]]: [[1985\u201386 Yugoslav Cup|1985\u201386]]\n\n'''AEK Athens'''\n*[[Super League Greece|Alpha Ethniki]]: [[1988\u201389 Alpha Ethniki|1988\u201389]], [[1991\u201392 Alpha Ethniki|1991\u201392]], [[1992\u201393 Alpha Ethniki|1992\u201393]], [[1993\u201394 Alpha Ethniki|1993\u201394]]\n*[[Greek Football Cup|Greek Cup]]: [[1995\u201396 Greek Cup|1995\u201396]]\n*[[Greek League Cup]]: [[Greek League Cup#Final|1989\u201390]] \n*[[Greek Super Cup]]: [[Greek Super Cup#Matches details|1989]]\n\n'''Olympiacos'''\n*[[Super League Greece|Alpha Ethniki]]: [[1996\u201397 Alpha Ethniki|1996\u201397]], [[1997\u201398 Alpha Ethniki|1997\u201398]], [[1998\u201399 Alpha Ethniki|1998\u201399]], [[2004\u201305 Alpha Ethniki|2004\u201305]]\n*[[Greek Football Cup|Greek Cup]]: [[1998\u201399 Greek Cup|1998\u201399]], [[2004\u201305 Greek Cup|2004\u201305]]\n\n'''PAOK'''\n*[[Greek Football Cup|Greek Cup]]: [[2000\u201301 Greek Cup|2000\u201301]]\n\n===Individual===\n*[[Greek football PSAP awards#Coaches Awards|Super League Greece Manager of the Season]]: [[1995\u201396 Alpha Ethniki|1995\u201396]], [[1997\u201398 Alpha Ethniki|1997\u201398]], [[1998\u201399 Alpha Ethniki|1998\u201399]], [[2000\u201301 Alpha Ethniki|2000\u201301]], [[2002\u201303 Alpha Ethniki|2002\u201303]], [[2007\u201308 Superleague Greece|2007\u201308]]\n\n==Other==\nBajevi\u0107 is famous for his nickname \"Princ sa Neretve\". On 10 September 2008, he received the Sport Association of the City of [[Mostar]] Award for his contribution in popularization and development of football and sport in general in his city.<ref>{{cite web|title=Priznanje Princu sa Neretve|url=http://sportsport.ba/bh_fudbal/priznanje-princu-sa-neretve/6857|work=sportsport.ba|accessdate=20 March 2013|language=Bosnian|date=10 September 2008}}</ref> On 20 February 2019, Bajevi\u0107 was awarded the 2018 [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]] Award for sports for his contribution in popularization and development of football in Bosnia and Herzegovina over the past years.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.klix.ba/sport/nogomet/dusanu-bajevicu-urucena-drzavna-nagrada-za-sport-u-2018-godini/190220051|title=Du\u0161anu Bajevi\u0107u uru\u010dena Dr\u017eavna nagrada za sport u 2018. godini|date=20 February 2019|accessdate=20 February 2019|language=Bosnian|author=K.H.|publisher=Klix.ba}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of football managers with most games]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* [https://gh.women.soccerway.com/coaches/duan-bajevi/214731/ Du\u0161an Bajevi\u0107] at Soccerway\n\n{{Current managers of UEFA national teams}}\n{{navboxes\n|title=Awards\n|bg=Gold\n|fg=Black\n|bordercolor=Black\n|list1=\n{{Yugoslav First League top scorers}}\n{{Yugoslav Footballer of the Year}}\n{{Super League Greece top scorers}}\n{{Greek Cup top scorers}}\n{{Super League Greece manager of the season}}\n}}\n{{navboxes\n|title=Yugoslavia squads\n|bg=#0c1c8c\n|fg=white\n|bordercolor=black\n|list1=\n{{Yugoslavia Squad 1974 World Cup}}\n}}\n{{navboxes\n|title=Managerial positions\n|list1=\n{{AEK Athens F.C. managers}}\n{{Olympiacos managers}}\n{{PAOK F.C. managers}}\n{{Red Star Belgrade managers}}\n{{Aris Thessaloniki F.C. managers}}\n{{AC Omonia managers}}\n{{Atromitos F.C. managers}}\n{{Bosnia and Herzegovina national football team managers}}\n}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bajevic, Dusan}}\n[[Category:1948 births]]\n[[Category:1974 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:AC Omonia managers]]\n[[Category:AEK Athens F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:AEK Athens F.C. players]]\n[[Category:AEK F.C. non-playing staff]]\n[[Category:Aris Thessaloniki F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:Bosnia and Herzegovina expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Bosnia and Herzegovina football managers]]\n[[Category:Bosnia and Herzegovina footballers]]\n[[Category:Bosnia and Herzegovina national football team managers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate football managers in Greece]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Greece]]\n[[Category:FK Vele\u017e Mostar managers]]\n[[Category:FK Vele\u017e Mostar players]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Naturalized citizens of Greece]]\n[[Category:Olympiacos F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:PAOK FC managers]]\n[[Category:Red Star Belgrade managers]]\n[[Category:Serbs of Bosnia and Herzegovina]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Mostar]]\n[[Category:Super League Greece managers]]\n[[Category:Super League Greece players]]\n[[Category:Yugoslav First League managers]]\n[[Category:Yugoslav First League players]]\n[[Category:Yugoslav football managers]]\n[[Category:Yugoslav footballers]]\n[[Category:Yugoslavia international footballers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Serbian association footballer and manager}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name           = Du\u0161an Bajevi\u0107\n| image          = Dusan Bajevic.jpg\n| image_size     = 160px\n| caption        = Bajevi\u0107 playing for [[Yugoslavia national football  team|Yugoslavia]] in a game against [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]] in the [[1974 FIFA World Cup]]  \n| fullname       = Du\u0161an Bajevi\u0107\n| height         = {{height|m=1.85}}\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1948|12|10|df=y}}\n| birth_place    = [[Mostar]], [[Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia|FPR Yugoslavia]]\n| position       = [[Forward (association football)#Striker|Striker]]\n| currentclub    = [[Bosnia and Herzegovina national football team|Bosnia and Herzegovina]] (manager)\n| years1         = 1966\u20131977 \n| clubs1         = [[FK Vele\u017e Mostar|Vele\u017e Mostar]]<ref name=\"iffhs\">[http://www.iffhs.de/?b4a390f03be4ac07cda17b45fdcdc3bfcdc0aec70aed02 IFFHS]. Iffhs.de. Retrieved on 3 January 2011.</ref>\n| caps1          = 277  \n| goals1         = 144  \n| years2         = 1977\u20131981\n| clubs2         = [[AEK Athens F.C.|AEK Athens]]<ref name=\"iffhs\"/>\n| caps2          = 106  \n| goals2         = 65   \n| years3         = 1981\u20131983\n| clubs3         = [[FK Vele\u017e Mostar|Vele\u017e Mostar]]<ref name=\"iffhs\"/>\n| caps3          = 45   \n| goals3         = 22   \n| totalcaps      = 478 \n| totalgoals     = 292\n| nationalyears1 = 1970\u20131977\n| nationalteam1  = [[Yugoslavia national football team|Yugoslavia]] \n| nationalcaps1  = 37  \n| nationalgoals1 = 29  \n| manageryears1  = 1984\u20131988  \n| managerclubs1  = [[FK Vele\u017e Mostar|Vele\u017e Mostar]]\n| manageryears2  = 1988\u20131996  \n| managerclubs2  = [[AEK Athens F.C.|AEK Athens]]\n| manageryears3  = 1996\u20131999  \n| managerclubs3  = [[Olympiacos F.C.|Olympiacos]]\n| manageryears4  = 2000\u20132002  \n| managerclubs4  = [[PAOK FC|PAOK]]\n| manageryears5  = 2002\u20132004  \n| managerclubs5  = [[AEK Athens F.C.|AEK Athens]]\n| manageryears6  = 2004\u20132005  \n| managerclubs6  = [[Olympiacos F.C.|Olympiacos]]\n| manageryears7  = 2006\u20132007  \n| managerclubs7  = [[Red Star Belgrade]]\n| manageryears8  = 2007\u20132008  \n| managerclubs8  = [[Aris Thessaloniki F.C.|Aris Thessaloniki]]\n| manageryears9  = 2008\u20132010  \n| managerclubs9  = [[AEK Athens F.C.|AEK Athens]]\n| manageryears10 = 2010\u20132011\n| managerclubs10 = [[AC Omonia|Omonia]]\n| manageryears11 = 2012 \n| managerclubs11 = [[Atromitos F.C.|Atromitos]]\n| manageryears12 = 2019\u2013\n| managerclubs12 = [[Bosnia and Herzegovina national football team|Bosnia and Herzegovina]]\n}}\n'''Du\u0161an \"Du\u0161ko\" Bajevi\u0107''' ({{lang-sr-cyr|\u0414\u0443\u0448\u0430\u043d \u0411\u0430\u0458\u0435\u0432\u0438\u045b}}, {{IPA-sh|d\u01d4\u0283an b\u01ceje\u028bit\u0255|pron}}; {{lang-gr|\u039d\u03c4\u03bf\u03cd\u03c3\u03b1\u03bd \u039c\u03c0\u03ac\u03b3\u03b5\u03b2\u03b9\u03c4\u03c2}}, ''Do\u00fasan B\u00e1yevits''; born 10 December 1948) is a Bosnian professional [[Manager (association football)|football manager]] and former player who is the head coach of the [[Bosnia and Herzegovina national football team|Bosnia and Herzegovina national team]].\n\nHe spent almost all of his career at hometown club [[FK Vele\u017e Mostar|Vele\u017e Mostar]] for who he played almost 400 games and scored 170 goals. He also played with [[AEK Athens F.C.|AEK Athens]] where he won the [[Super League Greece|Alpha Ethniki]] two times and the [[Greek Football Cup|Greek Cup]] once.\n\nAs a manager, Bajevi\u0107 has also had success, winning one [[Yugoslav Cup]] with Vele\u017e, four [[Super League Greece|Greek league title]]s, one [[Greek Football Cup|Greek Cup]], one [[Greek League Cup]] and one [[Greek Super Cup]] with [[AEK Athens F.C.|AEK Athens]], then four Greek league titles and two Greek Cups with [[Olympiacos F.C.|Olympiacos]] and one Greek Cup with [[PAOK FC|PAOK]].\n\n==Club career==\nBajevi\u0107 was the total player. He played almost 400 games for local club [[FK Vele\u017e Mostar|Vele\u017e Mostar]] where he scored 170 goals. His coach was [[Sulejman Rebac]]. He stayed in Vele\u017e from 1966 to 1977 before going to [[AEK Athens F.C.|AEK Athens]], where he won the [[Superleague Greece|Greek championship]] twice. He is one of the most controversial figures in the history of the club. Bajevi\u0107 was a successful player, loved by AEK's fans who gave him the nickname \"'''Prince'''\" (''\u03a0\u03c1\u03af\u03b3\u03ba\u03b7\u03c0\u03b1\u03c2'').\n\nHe joined the team in 1977 along with other great players of the era and won two championships and one cup title. His combination with [[Thomas Mavros]] was one of the best in Europe and one of the club's most beloved scoring duo. Bajevi\u0107 was also the league's top scorer during the [[1979\u201380 Alpha Ethniki|1979\u201380 season]].\n\nHe came back to Vele\u017e in 1981 and stayed to 1983 before retiring. During his career, He was together with [[Slobodan Santra\u010d]] the best goalscorer in the [[1969\u201370 Yugoslav First League]] season, scoring 20 goals. Bajevi\u0107 is remembered as \"The Prince of Neretva\" and was part of the Vele\u017e three known as the \"Mostar BMV\" (Bajevi\u0107, [[Enver Mari\u0107|Mari\u0107]] and [[Franjo Vladi\u0107|Vladi\u0107]]) during the 1960s, 1970s and 1980s.\n\n==International career==\t\nBajevi\u0107 played for the [[Yugoslavia national football team|Yugoslavia national team]] in the [[1974 FIFA World Cup]] where he scored three goals against [[DR Congo national football team|Zaire]]. He scored 29 times and earend 37 caps for Yugoslavia during his international career which spanned for seven years, from 1970 to 1977.\n\n==Managerial career==\n===Vele\u017e Mostar===\nAfter ending his football career in 1983, Bajevi\u0107 took over the role as manager of [[FK Vele\u017e Mostar|Vele\u017e]]. He led the team to win the [[Yugoslav Cup]] in 1986 by defeating [[Dinamo Zagreb]] 3\u20131 in the final. The next season Vele\u017e finished the league in second spot and Bajevi\u0107 went to Greece to manage [[AEK Athens F.C.|AEK Athens]].\n\n===AEK Athens===\nHe took over AEK's head coaching position in 1988. During his first season in charge ([[Alpha Ethniki 1988\u201389|1988\u201389]]), he managed to lead the team to an unexpected championship, delivering the league title to the club after a ten-year drought since he last won it as a player. He then went on to win three consecutive championships ([[Alpha Ethniki 1991-92|1992]], [[Alpha Ethniki 1992-93|1993]], [[Alpha Ethniki 1993-94|1994]]), one Greek Super Cup (1989), one League Cup (1990), one Pre-Mediterranean Cup (1991) and one Greek Cup ([[Greek Cup 1995-96|1996]]).\n\nThe club also had several decent campaigns in Europe under his management. Namely, they reached the [[UEFA Champions League|European Cup]] last 16 once ([[1989\u201390 European Cup|1990]], and the [[UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] last 16 twice ([[1992\u201393 UEFA Champions League|1993]]) and [[1994\u201395 UEFA Champions League|1995]]), the [[UEFA Cup Winners' Cup|Cup Winners' Cup]] last 16 once ([[1995\u201396 UEFA Cup Winners' Cup|1996]]) and the [[UEFA Europa League|UEFA Cup]] last 16 once ([[1991\u201392 UEFA Cup|1992]]).\n\n===Olympiacos===\nIn 1996, after eight glorious seasons at AEK, Bajevi\u0107 moved to [[Olympiacos F.C.|Olympiacos]], bringing great fan hostility upon himself from AEK supporters. While he was Olympiacos' manager, Olympiacos won their first [[Alpha Ethniki|championship]] in 1997 after ten sterile years, and became champions for three consecutive times. In 1999, Olympiacos won [[Double (association football)|the Double]] and, for the first and only time in their history, reached the [[UEFA Champions League]] quarter finals.\n\nIn the [[1996\u201397 Alpha Ethniki|1996\u201397]] season, Bajevi\u0107 led Olympiacos to the championship after 10 years, putting an end to the \"stone years'. This season, the team ended the [[Alpha Ethniki|League]] with a 12 points difference from [[AEK Athens F.C.|AEK Athens]], and 20 points difference from [[Panathinaikos F.C.|Panathinaikos]].\n\nThe next season, [[Alpha Ethniki 1997-98|1997\u201398]], Olympiacos participated for first time in the [[UEFA Champions League]] ending with a 3rd place in the group. In the Alpha Ethniki, Bajevi\u0107's team along with AEK and Panathinaikos were too close in the table, but finally Olympiacos made an important away win against Panathinaikos (0\u20132) and celebrated the second consecutive championship, with three points difference from Panathinaikos.\n\n1998\u201399 was a very successful season. Olympiacos reached the [[UEFA Champions League]] quarter finals, losing to [[Juventus]] (1\u20132 loss in Italy and 1\u20131 in the [[Olympic Stadium (Athens)|Olympic Stadium]]). They also won the domestic [[Double (association football)|double]]. In the league they ended with 10 points difference from AEK and 11 from Panathinaikos. In the [[Greek Cup 1998-99|Cup]], Olympiacos won 2\u20130, beating rivals Panathinaikos.\n\nThe fans had great expectations for the 1999\u201300 season with the additions of [[Giovanni Silva de Oliveira|Giovanni]] and [[Zlatko Zahovi\u010d]] to the squad, but Bajevi\u0107's team only achieved a 3rd place in the [[UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] group stage. The head coach was sacked on 11 November 1999, despite Olympiacos holding the top spot in the [[Alpha Ethniki 1999-2000|league]] at the time.\n\n===PAOK===\nBajevi\u0107 wasn't out of a job for long, moving [[Geography of Greece|north]] to the region of [[Macedonia (Greece)|Macedonia]] and its capital [[Thessaloniki]], where he had a decent spell at financially strapped [[PAOK FC|PAOK]]. During his stay at the club, he won the Greek Cup in 2001 (after a near-thirty year wait) beating \u039flympiakos 2\u20134 in Athens in a game in which his team delivered very high quality football.\n\n===AEK, second time===\nIn the summer of 2002, Bajevi\u0107 returned to AEK. Fans were bitterly divided among those who accepted him and those who couldn't forgive his defection to Olympiacos. The latter made his life a living hell. In the [[2002\u201303 UEFA Champions League|2002\u201303]] Champions League, AEK became the first and only team to collect six ties out of six games in the group phase and ended up at third position. A notable match was the 3\u20133 draw against reigning European champions [[Real Madrid]] at the [[Nikos Goumas Stadium]] and another 2\u20132 draw against [[Real Madrid]] coming back from 2\u20130 down at the Bernabeu in Madrid.\n\nStill, the antagonism with a section of AEK fans persisted. During a league match against [[Iraklis Thessaloniki F.C.|Iraklis]] on 25 January 2004, Bajevi\u0107 decided he had enough abuse and with no prior warning left the bench and resigned while the game was still in first half.\n\n===Olympiacos, second time===\nIn 2004, he returned to Olympiacos, where he won the double again. Also, his team got very close to the second round of the Champions League by collecting ten points, however the defeat against [[Liverpool F.C.]] with 3\u20131 in the last game stopped them not making it to the next round. Olympiacos went as far as the fourth round of the UEFA Cup. Despite these good results, he quit, mainly due to the pressure from Gate 7 fans who were not satisfied with the team's way of playing, although the majority of the fans were on his side.\n\n===Red Star Belgrade===\nOn 25 May 2006, Bajevi\u0107 became the coach of the former European Cup champion [[Red Star Belgrade]]. He was brought in by club president [[Dragan Stojkovi\u0107]] as a replacement to recently departed [[Walter Zenga]], with the appointment generally welcomed by club's fans due to Bajevi\u0107's glowing reputation as an experienced coach with plenty of success from the Greek league.\n\nThe expectations were also plentiful as Red Star, [[First League of Serbia and Montenegro|Serbia-Montenegro league]] champion, was getting ready to start [[2006\u201307 UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] [[2006\u201307 UEFA Champions League qualifying rounds|qualifying]]. After easily progressing from the initial stage versus Irish champions [[Cork City F.C.|Cork City]], they were drawn against powerhouse [[AC Milan]] in the final qualifying round, putting up decent resistance en route to 1\u20133 aggregate loss. Despite the failure to get into the Champions League, many still took some positives from the Milan clash, however things were different when Bajevi\u0107's squad got eliminated from the [[2006\u201307 UEFA Cup|UEFA Cup]] in the first round by [[FC Slovan Liberec|Slovan Liberec]] with embarrassing ease (1\u20134 on aggregate, including the 1\u20132 loss at home) thus failing to reach the group stage.\n\nIn contrast to European failures, the domestic league form was satisfactory with Bajevi\u0107 leading the team to top of the league with 14 points in spare at the winter break. However, the second part of the season began with an inexplicable dip in form. The slide continued and on 24 February 2007 Red Star lost 4\u20132 to eternal rivals FK Partizan. A few days later on 27 February 2007, angry fans made damage to Bajevi\u0107's club-issued Toyota SUV by slaming a brick through its side window while the car was parked at the Markana stadium parking lot during Bajevi\u0107's guest appearance on SOS kanal TV station.<ref>[http://www.nezavisne.com/sport/ostali/6506/Bajevicu-razbijen-terenac.html Bajevi\u0107u razbijen terenac]; ''Nezavisne novine'', 27 February 2007</ref>\n\nThe end of Bajevi\u0107's stint with Red Star came in shocking fashion on 10 March 2007 during a league match versus [[FK Vojvodina]]. Red Star was down 0\u20132 at home, prompting the fans to start chanting \"Du\u0161an leave\". Soon after the chant was picked up by the majority of the north stand where the [[Delije|club's most loyal supporters]] gather, Bajevi\u0107 decided to walk out on the team in the middle of the match, leaving the pitch in 70th minute.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/football/2007/mar/14/europeanfootball.sport Red Star's lustre fading fast as Bajevic snaps again];Jonathan Wilson's Blog @ guardian.co.uk, 14 March 2007</ref> The match finished 0\u20133, shrinking Red Star's lead at the top of the table to only 6 points. Bajevi\u0107's overall league record at the helm of Red Star during [[2006\u201307 Serbian Superliga|2006\u201307 season]] was 14 league wins, 3 draws, and 3 losses.\n\n===Aris===\nOn 7 September 2007, Bajevi\u0107 signed a 3-year contract with [[Aris Thessaloniki F.C.|Aris Thessaloniki]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.arisfc.gr/index.php?SCREEN=trainer&TrainerID=5|title=Profile in Aris official website|publisher=|accessdate=31 March 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402090810/http://www.arisfc.gr/index.php?SCREEN=trainer&TrainerID=5|archive-date=2 April 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\nDuring the [[2007\u201308 Alpha Ethniki|2007\u201308]] season, when he was the head coach of [[Aris Thessaloniki F.C.|Aris Thessaloniki]], the team played superb football. Aris reached both a respectable 4th place in the [[Greek Super League]] and reached the [[Greek Cup]] final, where the team was beaten by Greek champions [[Olympiacos F.C.]] with the score of 2\u20130. On 1 July 2008, he decided to resign, allegedly because Aris president Labros Skordas demanded that he bench star defender [[Avraam Papadopoulos]], after the latter rejected a contract extension.\n\nIn the UEFA Cup, Aris made excellent performances, eliminating [[Real Zaragoza]] and beating 3\u20130 Bajevi\u0107's old club Red Star Belgrade at home. Although, draws with [[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton]] and [[SC Braga]] and a 6\u20130 away loss to [[F.C. Bayern Munich|Bayern]] at Munich ended the team's dreams for qualification.\n\nAfter his resignation, he was immediately related with [[Panathinaikos FC|Panathinaikos]], while there were reports that there was a contract to be pented by the side of Bajevi\u0107. But he finally decided not to join the team, which eventually appointed [[Henk ten Cate]].\nBy the end of October, when the team of Panathinaikos was totally under-performing, and while ten Cate was on the verge of being sacked, the football manager of Panathinaikos, [[Kostas Antoniou]] was said to have asked once again Bajevi\u0107 to become the coach of the greens, but both sides rejected this relation.\n\n===AEK, third time===\nOn 21 November 2008, Bajevi\u0107 made his second return to AEK<ref>[http://www.aekfc.gr/index.asp?a_id=74&n_id=4638 Bajevic returns to AEK] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120214174700/http://www.aekfc.gr/index.asp?a_id=74&n_id=4638 |date=14 February 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/footballeurope/news/kind=2/newsid=776619.html|title=AEK turn to familiar face Bajevi\u0107|publisher=|accessdate=31 March 2018}}</ref> together with two other former players of AEK, [[Stelios Manolas]] in the position of the technical director and [[Lysandros Georgamlis]] as assistant coach.\n\nIn his first interview since being re-appointed as the head coach of AEK, Bajevi\u0107 covered a range of issues including the squad he had inherited, his ambitions for the remainder of what has so far been a difficult season, the possibility of a return to the club's symbolic home ground\u2014the Nikos Goumas Stadium at Nea Philadelphia\u2014and about his well-documented relationship with the fans.\n\nOn a possible return of AEK returning to the [[Nikos Goumas Stadium]], Bajevi\u0107 said: \"It is my home because as a player and a manager I lived there\", \"I'm not the only one who wants a stadium at [[Nea Philadelphia]] \u2013 there are a lot of others who want it there.\"\nHe then went on to discuss his relationship with the fans and Original 21, \"I have said sorry to whoever I aggrieved and I say sorry again to everyone\", \"We can't afford to talk about it now though. We all love AEK. We need to forget the good and the bad and look forward\".\n\nHis first game in charge was a 1\u20131 draw against [[OFI Crete]] in [[Crete]] on 23 November 2008. The first season in his third spell in-charge of \"Dikefalos Aetos\" brought ups and downs. AEK in the league, finished 4th, thus qualifying for the seasons annual play-offs in which AEK finished 2nd meaning qualification for next seasons [[Europa League]]. Bajevi\u0107 managed to get AEK to the Greek Cup Final where they came up short handed as they lost 16\u201315 on penalties to [[Olympiacos F.C.|Olympiacos]] after the game finished 4\u20134 after extra time.\n\nOn 7 August 2010 Bajevi\u0107 faced one of his worst moments in football. A section of AEK fans physically assaulted him following a friendly-game loss against to second division side [[Kallithea F.C.]].<ref>[http://football.uk.reuters.com/leagues/european/news/2010/08/07/LDE6760A2.php AEK Athens coach Bajevic attacked by fans] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120226110608/http://football.uk.reuters.com/leagues/european/news/2010/08/07/LDE6760A2.php |date=26 February 2012 }}; Reuters, 7 August 2010</ref> Bajevi\u0107 fell to the ground after being punched by the fans who surrounded the coach as he attempted to leave the pitch at the [[Gregoris Lambrakis Stadium]] following the 2\u20131 defeat.<ref>{{YouTube|sO1UMl47FQI|Bajevic assaulted}}; 7 August 2010</ref>\n\nIt was feared that the incidents in Kallithea would lead to Bajevi\u0107's resignation, but due to overwhelming support from AEK management, players, and the majority of AEK fans, Bajevi\u0107 was convinced to stay on with the club.\nThe video of the attack caused a worldwide shock, with many foreign media sources commenting on the lack of progress in stamping-out hooliganism at Greek football matches.<ref>[http://fourfourtwo.com/news/restofeurope/60797/default.aspx AEK coach Bajevic attacked by fans]. FourFourTwo. Retrieved on 3 January 2011.</ref>\n\nMonth-and-a-half later on 26 September 2010, Bajevi\u0107 resigned as head coach of AEK, following the 3\u20131 away defeat to [[Olympiakos Volou]] in the Greek Superleague.\n\n===AC Omonia Nicosia===\nOn 13 October 2010, Bajevi\u0107 signed a contract with Cyprus's club, [[AC Omonia]] Nicosia,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cyprusweekly.com.cy/main/82,1,286,0,13305-.aspx|title=Bajevic to lead Omonia|accessdate=31 March 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110926230427/http://www.cyprusweekly.com.cy/main/82,1,286,0,13305-.aspx|archive-date=26 September 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref> following the resignation of its predecessor Takis Lemonis. The managerial crew was also consisted of two training assistants, assistant coach [[Lysandros Georgamlis]] and physical fitness coach Dimitris Mpourouzikas. The first game with Bajevi\u0107 sitting on the club's bench was scheduled on Monday, 18 October against [[Olympiakos Nicosia]].\n\n===Return to Greece===\nOn 2 June 2012, Bajevi\u0107 agreed on a 2-year contract with Greek Cup finalist [[Atromitos F.C.|Atromitos]]. He came to replace [[Giorgos Donis]] who resigned some days before. The Bosnian coach returned to Greece after 1.5-year in order to manage the 5th Greek club in his career.\n\nHe resigned his post on 22 December 2012 following the third round elimination in the [[2012\u201313 Greek Football Cup|Greek Cup]] to second-tier [[Olympiakos Volou 1937 F.C.|Olympiakos Volou]] that progressed on away goals following the injury time equalizer by A\u00f1ete.<ref>[http://www.b92.net/sport/fudbal/vesti.php?yyyy=2012&mm=12&dd=22&nav_id=671431 Ostavka Bajevi\u0107a u Atromitosu];B92, 22 December 2012</ref> In the league, Atromitos was holding the 4th spot after 15 matches.\n\n===Bosnia and Herzegovina===\nOn 21 December 2019, Bajevi\u0107 was named new head coach of the [[Bosnia and Herzegovina national football team|Bosnia and Herzegovina national team]], with a contract until the end of [[UEFA Euro 2020]] should he qualify through the [[UEFA Euro 2020 qualifying play-offs]] in September 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.klix.ba/sport/nogomet/dusan-bajevic-je-novi-selektor-nogometne-reprezentacije-bih/191221014|title=Du\u0161an Bajevi\u0107 je novi selektor nogometne reprezentacije BiH|date=21 December 2019|accessdate=21 December 2019|language=Bosnian|author=E.B.|publisher=Klix.ba}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.klix.ba/sport/nogomet/baraz-za-evropsko-prvenstvo-izmedju-bih-i-sjeverne-irske-igra-se-u-junu/200317151|title=Bara\u017e za Evropsko prvenstvo izme\u0111u BiH i Sjeverne Irske igra se u junu|date=17 March 2020|accessdate=17 March 2020|language=Bosnian|author=N.K.|publisher=Klix.ba}}</ref>\n\n==Administrative work==\n\n===Football Federation of BiH: 2011\u20132012===\nOn 1 April 2011, after the [[Football Federation of Bosnia and Herzegovina]] was suspended for two months from all international competitions by [[FIFA]] and [[UEFA]], Bajevi\u0107  became part of its \"normalization committee\", an [[interim]] [[committee]] created to run the Bosnian Football Federation, and whose main purpose was to have the Federation approve the changes required by FIFA for the suspension to be lifted.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sportsport.ba/bh_fudbal/barbarez-moramo-iskoristiti-pruzenu-priliku/55470|title=Barbarez: Moramo iskoristiti pru\u017eenu priliku|publisher=|accessdate=31 March 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"balkaninsight.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.balkaninsight.com/en/article/fifa-and-uefa-to-name-the-emergency-body-to-save-bosnia-s-football|title=FIFA Names Ivica Osim Head of Bosnian Football :: Balkan Insight|accessdate=18 April 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Managerial statistics==\n{{updated|22 December 2012}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" tyle=\"text-align: center\"\n|+ Managerial record by team and tenure\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Team\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Nat\n!rowspan=\"2\"|From\n!rowspan=\"2\"|To\n!colspan=\"5\"|Record\n|-\n!{{Tooltip|G|Games managed}}\n!{{Tooltip|W|Games won}}\n!{{Tooltip|D|Games drawn}}\n!{{Tooltip|L|Games lost}}\t\n!{{Tooltip|Win %|Winning percentage}}\n|-\n|align=center|[[FK Vele\u017e Mostar|Vele\u017e Mostar]]\n|align=center|{{flagicon|YUG}}\n|align=center|1 July 1984\n|align=center|30 June 1988\n{{WDL|152|66|42|44}}\n|-\n|align=center|[[AEK Athens F.C.|AEK Athens]]\n|align=center|{{flagicon|GRE}}\n|align=center|1 July 1988\n|align=center|26 June 1996\n{{WDL|372|217|77|78}}\n|-\n|align=center|[[Olympiacos F.C.|Olympiacos]]\n|align=center|{{flagicon|GRE}}\n|align=center|26 June 1996\n|align=center|10 November 1999\n{{WDL|157|113|22|22}}\n|-\n|align=center|[[PAOK FC|PAOK]]\n|align=center|{{flagicon|GRE}}\n|align=center|1 January 2000\n|align=center|8 May 2002\n{{WDL|117|63|28|26}}\n|-\n|align=center|[[AEK Athens F.C.|AEK Athens]]\n|align=center|{{flagicon|GRE}}\n|align=center|20 May 2002\n|align=center|25 January 2004\n{{WDL|82|45|23|14}}\n|-\n|align=center|[[Olympiacos F.C.|Olympiacos]]\n|align=center|{{flagicon|GRE}}\n|align=center|1 July 2004\n|align=center|30 June 2005\n{{WDL|51|31|10|10}}\n|-\n|align=center|[[Red Star Belgrade]]\n|align=center|{{flagicon|SRB}}\n|align=center|1 July 2006\n|align=center|10 March 2007\n{{WDL|28|18|3|7}}\n|-\n|align=center|[[Aris Thessaloniki F.C.|Aris Thessaloniki]]\n|align=center|{{flagicon|GRE}}\n|align=center|7 September 2007\n|align=center|30 June 2008\n{{WDL|49|22|13|14}}\n|-\n|align=center|[[AEK Athens F.C.|AEK Athens]]\n|align=center|{{flagicon|GRE}}\n|align=center|21 November 2008\n|align=center|27 September 2010\n{{WDL|84|39|23|22}}\n|-\n|align=center|[[AC Omonia|Omonia]]\n|align=center|{{flagicon|CYP}}\n|align=center|13 October 2010\n|align=center|14 April 2011\n{{WDL|29|18|8|3}}\n|-\n|align=center|[[Atromitos F.C.|Atromitos]]\n|align=center|{{flagicon|GRE}}\n|align=center|2 June 2012\n|align=center|23 December 2012\n{{WDL|19|6|10|3}}\n|-\n|align=center|[[Bosnia and Herzegovina national football team|Bosnia and Herzegovina]]\n|align=center|\u2014\n|align=center|21 December 2019\n|align=center|Present\n{{WDL|0|0|0|0}}\n|-\n!colspan=4|Total\n{{WDLtot|1140|638|260|242}}\n|}\n\n==Honours==\n===Player===\n'''AEK Athens'''\n*[[Super League Greece|Alpha Ethniki]]: [[1977\u201378 Alpha Ethniki|1977\u201378]], [[1977\u201378 Alpha Ethniki|1978\u201379]] \n*[[Greek Football Cup|Greek Cup]]: [[1977\u201378 Greek Cup|1977\u201378]] \n\n===Individual===\n'''Awards'''\n*[[Croatian Footballer of the Year#List of winners|Yugoslav Footballer of the Year]]: 1972\n\n'''Performance'''\n*[[Yugoslav First League]] Top Goalscorer: [[1969\u201370 Yugoslav First League|1969\u201370]] (20 goals)\n*[[List of top goalscorers in Superleague Greece by season|Alpha Ethniki Top Goalscorer]]: [[1979\u201380 Alpha Ethniki|1979\u201380]] (25 goals)\n*[[Greek Football Cup|Greek Cup]] Top Goalscorer: [[1977\u201378 Alpha Ethniki|1977\u201378]], [[1978\u201379 Alpha Ethniki|1978\u201379]]\n*[[Brazil_Independence_Cup#Goalscorers|Brazil Independence Cup 1972 Top Goalscorer ]]\n\n===Manager===\n'''Vele\u017e Mostar'''\n*[[Yugoslav Cup]]: [[1985\u201386 Yugoslav Cup|1985\u201386]]\n\n'''AEK Athens'''\n*[[Super League Greece|Alpha Ethniki]]: [[1988\u201389 Alpha Ethniki|1988\u201389]], [[1991\u201392 Alpha Ethniki|1991\u201392]], [[1992\u201393 Alpha Ethniki|1992\u201393]], [[1993\u201394 Alpha Ethniki|1993\u201394]]\n*[[Greek Football Cup|Greek Cup]]: [[1995\u201396 Greek Cup|1995\u201396]]\n*[[Greek League Cup]]: [[Greek League Cup#Final|1989\u201390]] \n*[[Greek Super Cup]]: [[Greek Super Cup#Matches details|1989]]\n\n'''Olympiacos'''\n*[[Super League Greece|Alpha Ethniki]]: [[1996\u201397 Alpha Ethniki|1996\u201397]], [[1997\u201398 Alpha Ethniki|1997\u201398]], [[1998\u201399 Alpha Ethniki|1998\u201399]], [[2004\u201305 Alpha Ethniki|2004\u201305]]\n*[[Greek Football Cup|Greek Cup]]: [[1998\u201399 Greek Cup|1998\u201399]], [[2004\u201305 Greek Cup|2004\u201305]]\n\n'''PAOK'''\n*[[Greek Football Cup|Greek Cup]]: [[2000\u201301 Greek Cup|2000\u201301]]\n\n===Individual===\n*[[Greek football PSAP awards#Coaches Awards|Super League Greece Manager of the Season]]: [[1995\u201396 Alpha Ethniki|1995\u201396]], [[1997\u201398 Alpha Ethniki|1997\u201398]], [[1998\u201399 Alpha Ethniki|1998\u201399]], [[2000\u201301 Alpha Ethniki|2000\u201301]], [[2002\u201303 Alpha Ethniki|2002\u201303]], [[2007\u201308 Superleague Greece|2007\u201308]]\n\n==Other==\nBajevi\u0107 is famous for his nickame \"Princ sa Neretve\". On 10 September 2008, he received the Sport Association of the City of [[Mostar]] Award for his contribution in popularization and development of football and sport in general in his city.<ref>{{cite web|title=Priznanje Princu sa Neretve|url=http://sportsport.ba/bh_fudbal/priznanje-princu-sa-neretve/6857|work=sportsport.ba|accessdate=20 March 2013|language=Bosnian|date=10 September 2008}}</ref> On 20 February 2019, Bajevi\u0107 was awarded the 2018 [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]] Award for sports for his contribution in popularization and development of football in Bosnia and Herzegovina over the past years.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.klix.ba/sport/nogomet/dusanu-bajevicu-urucena-drzavna-nagrada-za-sport-u-2018-godini/190220051|title=Du\u0161anu Bajevi\u0107u uru\u010dena Dr\u017eavna nagrada za sport u 2018. godini|date=20 February 2019|accessdate=20 February 2019|language=Bosnian|author=K.H.|publisher=Klix.ba}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of football managers with most games]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n*[https://gh.women.soccerway.com/coaches/duan-bajevi/214731/ Du\u0161an Bajevi\u0107] at Soccerway\n\n{{Current managers of UEFA national teams}}\n{{navboxes\n|title=Awards\n|bg=Gold\n|fg=Black\n|bordercolor=Black\n|list1=\n{{Yugoslav First League top scorers}}\n{{Yugoslav Footballer of the Year}}\n{{Super League Greece top scorers}}\n{{Greek Cup top scorers}}\n{{Super League Greece manager of the season}}\n}}\n{{navboxes\n|title=Yugoslavia squads\n|bg=#0c1c8c\n|fg=white\n|bordercolor=black\n|list1=\n{{Yugoslavia Squad 1974 World Cup}}\n}}\n{{navboxes\n|title=Managerial positions\n|list1=\n{{AEK Athens F.C. managers}}\n{{Olympiacos managers}}\n{{PAOK F.C. managers}}\n{{Red Star Belgrade managers}}\n{{Aris Thessaloniki F.C. managers}}\n{{AC Omonia managers}}\n{{Atromitos F.C. managers}}\n{{Bosnia and Herzegovina national football team managers}}\n}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bajevic, Dusan}}\n[[Category:1948 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Mostar]]\n[[Category:Serbs of Bosnia and Herzegovina]]\n[[Category:Yugoslav footballers]]\n[[Category:Bosnia and Herzegovina footballers]]\n[[Category:Yugoslav football managers]]\n[[Category:Bosnia and Herzegovina football managers]]\n[[Category:FK Vele\u017e Mostar players]]\n[[Category:AEK Athens F.C. players]]\n[[Category:AEK Athens F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:FK Vele\u017e Mostar managers]]\n[[Category:Olympiacos F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:PAOK FC managers]]\n[[Category:Red Star Belgrade managers]]\n[[Category:Aris Thessaloniki F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:AC Omonia managers]]\n[[Category:Bosnia and Herzegovina national football team managers]]\n[[Category:1974 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:Yugoslavia international footballers]]\n[[Category:Bosnia and Herzegovina expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Greece]]\n[[Category:Naturalized citizens of Greece]]\n[[Category:Yugoslav First League players]]\n[[Category:Yugoslav First League managers]]\n[[Category:Super League Greece players]]\n[[Category:Super League Greece managers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate football managers in Greece]]\n[[Category:AEK F.C. non-playing staff]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n", "name_user": "DocWatson42", "label": "safe", "comment": "Performed minor cleanup.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Du%C5%A1an_Bajevi%C4%87"}
{"title_page": "Dwight D. Eisenhower Presidential Library, Museum and Boyhood Home", "text_new": "{{short description|Presidential library and museum for U.S. President Dwight D. Eisenhower, located in Abilene, Kansas}}\n{{Infobox building\n| name = Dwight Eisenhower Presidential Library, Museum and Boyhood Home\n| logo = Official logo of the Dwight D. Eisenhower Presidential Library.svg\n| logo_size = 120px\n| logo_alt = \n| logo_caption  = \n| image = Eisenhower library.jpg\n| image_size = 250px\n| image_alt = \n| image_caption = The Eisenhower Library\n| map_type = USA Kansas#USA\n| map_size = 300\n| map_caption = \n| location = [[Abilene, Kansas]], USA\n| coordinates = {{Coord|38|54|44|N|97|12|39|W|type:landmark_region:US-KS|format=dms|display=inline,title|name=Eisenhower Library}}\n| inauguration_date = \n| namesake = [[Dwight D. Eisenhower]]\n| construction_start_date = \n| completion_date = \n| cost = \n| size = \n| management = [[National Archives and Records Administration|NARA]]\n| architect =  \n| website = [https://www.eisenhower.archives.gov Eisenhower Library, Museum and Boyhood Home]\n}} \n{{Eisenhower series}}\n\nThe '''Dwight D. Eisenhower Presidential Library, Museum and Boyhood Home''' is the [[presidential library]] and museum of [[Dwight D. Eisenhower|Dwight David Eisenhower]], the [[List of Presidents of the United States|34th]] [[President of the United States]] (1953\u20131961), located in his hometown of [[Abilene, Kansas]]. The museum also includes [[Eisenhower Home|his boyhood home]], where he lived from 1898 until being appointed to [[United States Military Academy|West Point]] in 1911,<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.pantagraph.com/abilene-site-celebrates-eisenhower-s-life/article_62ed9d6f-c584-58c6-819c-247a55999bb2.html| title=Abilene Site Celebrates Eisenhower's Life| last=Tanner| first=Beccy|date=December 9, 2015| website=Pantagraph.com| publisher=The Pantagraph| access-date=March 3, 2017}}</ref> and his final resting place. It is one of the thirteen presidential libraries under the auspices of the [[National Archives and Records Administration]] (NARA).\n\nAdmission to the Visitor Center, Place of Meditation (gravesite), and the archives is free. Admission to the museum is $20 for adults and includes a tour of the Boyhood Home. The complex is open every day except New Year's Day, Thanksgiving and Christmas.<ref>{{cite web|title=Hours and Admissions|url=https://www.eisenhower.archives.gov/visit_us/hours_admissions.html|website=Eisenhower Presidential Library|publisher=National Archives and Records Administration|accessdate=7 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe Eisenhower Presidential complex is only one of two whose creation preceded the close of a presidency, and while this is obviously the case with his boyhood home, construction of the library itself began in 1958, and the museum portion before he even took office, coinciding with the then-General's announcement of his presidential candidacy in June 1952.<ref>{{cite book|last=Pusey |first=Merlo J. |date=1956 |title=Eisenhower: The President |url=https://archive.org/details/eisenhowerthepre002645mbp |location=New York  |publisher=The MacMillan Company |isbn=9780758190826}}</ref>\n\n===Eisenhower Foundation===\nAs [[World War II]] came to an end, local admirers of the [[Supreme Headquarters Allied Expeditionary Force|Supreme Commander of Allied forces in Europe]] decided to honor him with a museum. In 1945, a non-profit foundation in his name was created to purchase his boyhood home and build the museum on the same property. It was to house artifacts from veterans, and the honors of Eisenhower in particular.<ref name=WHH>{{cite journal |last=Weissenbach |first=Karl |date=2016 |title=Dwight D. Eisenhower Presidential Library, Museum, and Boyhood Home |url= |journal=White House History |volume= |issue=40 |publisher= White House Historical Association |pages=45\u201349 |issn=0748-8114 |access-date= }}</ref> At the time, the General's mother [[Ida Stover Eisenhower|Ida]] was still alive and refused to sell the property. When she died in 1946, another purchase attempt was made. However, the fund-raising tactics of the foundation offended Eisenhower, and this almost scuttled the project. New fundraising rules were established for the Foundation after its discussion with Ike's youngest brother [[Milton S. Eisenhower|Milton]], and agreement by all the Eisenhower brothers.<ref name=WHH /> They ultimately donated the house to the Foundation, and the entire site, in south Abilene, later became the Eisenhower Presidential Center.<ref>{{cite book |last=Clotworthy |first=William G. |date=May 2008 |title=Homes and Libraries of the Presidents |url=http://www.mwpubco.com/titles/hlp.htm |location=Blacksburg, Virginia |publisher=The McDonald and Woodward Publishing Company |edition=3rd |pages=258\u20139 |isbn=0-939923-34-3}}</ref>\n\n===Construction of the Museum===\nMrs. Eisenhower's home opened to the public as a museum on June 22, 1947.<ref name=WHH /> and the cornerstone of an Eisenhower/World War II museum was laid in June 1952 by the General himself, just before he accepted the [[Draft Eisenhower movement|draft]] and formally announced his candidacy for President.\n\nThe museum was completed in 1954, and the President was in attendance when it was formally opened on November 11 of that year. He was impressed by the results, and told the leadership of the foundation that if they could raise the money to build a facility, he would donate his papers and other materials to it.\n\nA fundraising campaign launched in 2015 seeks to refresh and expand the museum's exhibits in 2018. If plans remain the same, the museum would be closed for about a year while the remainder of the site would remain open as usual.<ref>{{cite news| last=Tanner |first=Beccy |date=August 23, 2015 | title=Eisenhower Foundation Launches Fundraising Campaign to Update Abilene Exhibits|url=http://www.kansas.com/news/state/article31964796.html | work=The Wichita Eagle |location=Abilene, Kansas |access-date=March 4, 2017 }}</ref>\n\n===Construction and dedication of the library===\nWith the fundraising constraints on the foundation still in place in 1954, the [[Kansas Legislature]] took up the slack, authorizing a separate \"Eisenhower Presidential Library Commission,\" and over the next five years enough money was raised to begin construction. Again, President Eisenhower was present when ground was broken on October 13, 1959. The project took three years to complete, and [[Vice President of the United States|Vice President]] [[Lyndon B. Johnson]] joined the retired President Eisenhower at the dedication on May 1, 1962.<ref name=WHH />\n\nOperation of the site was turned over to the [[National Archives and Records Administration|NARA]] in 1966, when it became the fourth library in the system.\n\n==Campus==\nThe campus has five buildings:<ref>{{cite web|title=The Eisenhower Presidential Library & Museum|url=http://www.kansastravel.org/eisenhower.htm|last=Stokes |first=Keith |year=2016| website=KansasTravel.org|publisher=Keith Stokes|accessdate=October 7, 2014}}</ref><ref name=IlikeIke>{{cite news|last=Olsen |first=Karen Torme |title=After a Visit to Abilene, I Like Ike |date=June 17, 2016 |url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/lifestyles/travel/ct-eisenhower-museum-abilene-travel-0703-20160617-story.html |work=Chicago Tribune |location=Abilene, Kansas |access-date=March 5, 2017}}</ref>\n\n*'''The Library'''\n*'''The Museum''', restored and rededicated in 1971.\n*'''Visitors Center''', containing a gift shop and theater where a short film on the President is shown several times daily.\n*'''[[Eisenhower Home|Boyhood Home]]'''\n*'''A chapel''', known as \"The Place of Meditation;\" the final resting place of the president, the First Lady, and their first-born son, [[Doud Eisenhower]].\n\nAlso on the site:\n\n*'''A statue of General Eisenhower''' by Robert L. Dean, Jr., presented to the campus by the Harry and Edith Darby Foundation.\n*'''Five pylons''' inscribed with phrases commemorating Eisenhower's life from birth through the Presidency.\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:EisenhowerCenterGrounds060708a.JPG|Grounds as seen from approach to place of meditation\nFile:Eisenhower House.jpg|Front of Eisenhower boyhood home, southwest corner\nFile:EisenhowerHome1.jpg|Southeast corner of boyhood home\nFile:Eisenhower Statue Abilene Kansas.jpg|Eisenhower statue in \"Champion of Peace\" circle, with memorial pylons in background\nFile:Defense.gov photo essay 100508-D-7203C-007.jpg|Inside Museum lobby; [[United States Secretary of Defense|Defense Secretary]] [[Robert M. Gates|Robert Gates]] and Army Capt. Josh Mantz, 2010\nFile:Defense.gov photo essay 100508-D-7203C-005.jpg|Museum tour; Secretary Gates and Museum Director Karl Weissenbach, 2010\nFile:Eisenhower Resting Place.jpg|View from entry corridor of \"Place of Meditation\"\nFile:DDEisenhowerGrave3.jpg|Graves of Dwight D. Eisenhower, Doud Dwight Eisenhower and Mamie Eisenhower\nFile:DDEisenhowerGrave2.jpg|Front view of graves\nFile:DDEisenhowerGrave.jpg|Grave of Dwight D. Eisenhower\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.eisenhower.archives.gov Official site of the Eisenhower Library, Museum and Boyhood Home]\n*[http://www.eisenhowerfoundation.net/ The Eisenhower Foundation (Kansas) website]\n*[http://www.c-span.org/video/?151630-1/life-portrait-dwight-d-eisenhower \"Life Portrait of Dwight D. Eisenhower\"], from [[C-SPAN]]'s ''[[American Presidents: Life Portraits]]'', broadcast from the Eisenhower Presidential Library, Museum and Boyhood Home, October 25, 1999\n\n{{US presidential libraries}}\n{{Dwight D. Eisenhower|state=expanded}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Library buildings completed in 1962]]\n[[Category:Presidential libraries|Eisenhower, Dwight D.]]\n[[Category:Landmarks in Kansas]]\n[[Category:Dwight D. Eisenhower|Presidential Library]]\n[[Category:Museums in Dickinson County, Kansas]]\n[[Category:Biographical museums in Kansas]]\n[[Category:Presidential museums in the United States|Eisenhower, Dwight D.]]\n[[Category:Tombs of Presidents of the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Presidential library and museum for U.S. President Dwight D. Eisenhower, located in Abilene, Kansas}}\n{{Infobox building\n| name = Dwight Eisenhower Presidential Library, Museum and Boyhood Home\n| logo = Official logo of the Dwight D. Eisenhower Presidential Library.svg\n| logo_size = 120px\n| logo_alt = \n| logo_caption  = \n| image = Eisenhower library.jpg\n| image_size = 250px\n| image_alt = \n| image_caption = The Eisenhower Library\n| map_type = USA Kansas#USA\n| map_size = 300\n| map_caption = \n| location = [[Abilene, Kansas]], USA\n| coordinates = {{Coord|38|54|44|N|97|12|39|W|type:landmark_region:US-KS|format=dms|display=inline,title|name=Eisenhower Library}}\n| inauguration_date = \n| namesake = [[Dwight D. Eisenhower]]\n| construction_start_date = \n| completion_date = \n| cost = \n| size = \n| management = [[National Archives and Records Administration|NARA]]\n| architect =  \n| website = [https://www.eisenhower.archives.gov Eisenhower Library, Museum and Boyhood Home]\n}} \n{{Eisenhower series}}\n\nThe '''Dwight D. Eisenhower Presidential Library, Museum and Boyhood Home''' is the [[presidential library]] and museum of [[Dwight D. Eisenhower|Dwight David Eisenhower]], the [[List of Presidents of the United States|34th]] [[President of the United States]] (1953\u20131961), located in his hometown of [[Abilene, Kansas]]. The museum also includes [[Eisenhower Home|his boyhood home]], where he lived from 1898 until being appointed to [[United States Military Academy|West Point]] in 1911,<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.pantagraph.com/abilene-site-celebrates-eisenhower-s-life/article_62ed9d6f-c584-58c6-819c-247a55999bb2.html| title=Abilene Site Celebrates Eisenhower's Life| last=Tanner| first=Beccy|date=December 9, 2015| website=Pantagraph.com| publisher=The Pantagraph| access-date=March 3, 2017}}</ref> and his final resting place. It is one of the thirteen presidential libraries under the auspices of the [[National Archives and Records Administration]] (NARA).\n\nAdmission to the Visitor Center, Place of Meditation (gravesite), and the archives is free. Admission to the museum is $20 for adults and includes a tour of the Boyhood Home. The complex is open every day except New Year's Day, Thanksgiving and Christmas.<ref>{{cite web|title=Hours and Admissions|url=https://www.eisenhower.archives.gov/visit_us/hours_admissions.html|website=Eisenhower Presidential Library|publisher=National Archives and Records Administration|accessdate=7 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe Eisenhower Presidential complex is only one of two whose creation preceded the close of a presidency, and while this is obviously the case with his boyhood home, construction of the library itself began in 1958, and the museum portion before he even took office, coinciding with the then-General's announcement of his presidential candidacy in June 1952.<ref>{{cite book|last=Pusey |first=Merlo J. |date=1956 |title=Eisenhower: The President |url=https://archive.org/details/eisenhowerthepre002645mbp |location=New York  |publisher=The MacMillan Company |isbn=9780758190826}}</ref>\n\n===Eisenhower Foundation===\nAs [[World War II]] came to an end, local admirers of the [[Supreme Headquarters Allied Expeditionary Force|Supreme Commander of Allied forces in Europe]] decided to honor him with a museum. In 1945, a non-profit foundation in his name was created to purchase his boyhood home and build the museum on the same property. It was to house artifacts from veterans, and the honors of Eisenhower in particular.<ref name=WHH>{{cite journal |last=Weissenbach |first=Karl |date=2016 |title=Dwight D. Eisenhower Presidential Library, Museum, and Boyhood Home |url= |journal=White House History |volume= |issue=40 |publisher= White House Historical Association |pages=45\u201349 |issn=0748-8114 |access-date= }}</ref> At the time, the General's mother [[Ida Stover Eisenhower|Ida]] was still alive and refused to sell the property. When she died in 1946, another purchase attempt was made. However, the fund-raising tactics of the foundation offended Eisenhower, and this almost scuttled the project. New fundraising rules were established for the Foundation after its discussion with Ike's youngest brother [[Milton S. Eisenhower|Milton]], and agreement by all the Eisenhower brothers.<ref name=WHH /> They ultimately donated the house to the Foundation, and the entire site, in south Abilene, later became the Eisenhower Presidential Center.<ref>{{cite book |last=Clotworthy |first=William G. |date=May 2008 |title=Homes and Libraries of the Presidents |url=http://www.mwpubco.com/titles/hlp.htm |location=Blacksburg, Virginia |publisher=The McDonald and Woodward Publishing Company |edition=3rd |pages=258\u20139 |isbn=0-939923-34-3}}</ref>\n\n===Construction of the Museum===\nMrs. Eisenhower's home opened to the public as a museum on June 22, 1947.<ref name=WHH /> and the cornerstone of an Eisenhower/World War II museum was laid in June 1952 by the General himself, just before he accepted the [[Draft Eisenhower movement|draft]] and formally announced his candidacy for President.\n\nThe museum was completed in 1954, and the President was in attendance when it was formally opened on November 11 of that year. He was impressed by the results, and told the leadership of the foundation that if they could raise the money to build a facility, he would donate his papers and other materials to it.\n\nA fundraising campaign launched in 2015 seeks to refresh and expand the museum's exhibits in 2018. If plans remain the same, the museum would be closed for about a year while the remainder of the site would remain open as usual.<ref>{{cite news| last=Tanner |first=Beccy |date=August 23, 2015 | title=Eisenhower Foundation Launches Fundraising Campaign to Update Abilene Exhibits|url=http://www.kansas.com/news/state/article31964796.html | work=The Wichita Eagle |location=Abilene, Kansas |access-date=March 4, 2017 }}</ref>\n\n===Construction and dedication of the library===\nWith the fundraising constraints on the foundation still in place in 1954, the [[Kansas Legislature]] took up the slack, authorizing a separate \"Eisenhower Presidential Library Commission,\" and over the next five years enough money was raised to begin construction. Again, President Eisenhower was present when ground was broken on October 13, 1959. The project took three years to complete, and [[Vice President of the United States|Vice President]] [[Lyndon B. Johnson]] joined the retired President Eisenhower at the dedication on May 1, 1962.<ref name=WHH />\n\nOperation of the site was turned over to the [[National Archives and Records Administration|NARA]] in 1966, when it became the fourth library in the system.\n\n==Campus==\nThe campus has five buildings:<ref>{{cite web|title=The Eisenhower Presidential Library & Museum|url=http://www.kansastravel.org/eisenhower.htm|last=Stokes |first=Keith |year=2016| website=KansasTravel.org|publisher=Keith Stokes|accessdate=October 7, 2014}}</ref><ref name=IlikeIke>{{cite news|last=Olsen |first=Karen Torme |title=After a Visit to Abilene, I Like Ike |date=June 17, 2016 |url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/lifestyles/travel/ct-eisenhower-museum-abilene-travel-0703-20160617-story.html |work=Chicago Tribune |location=Abilene, Kansas |access-date=March 5, 2017}}</ref>\n\n*'''The Library'''\n*'''The Museum''', restored and rededicated in 1971.\n*'''Visitors Center''', containing a gift shop and theater where a short film on the President is shown several times daily.\n*'''[[Eisenhower Home|Boyhood Home]]'''\n*'''A chapel''', known as \"The Place of Meditation;\" the final resting place of the president, the First Lady, and their first-born son, [[Doud Eisenhower]].\n\nAlso on the site:\n\n*'''A statue of General Eisenhower''' by Robert L. Dean, Jr., presented to the campus by the Harry and Edith Darby Foundation.\n*'''Five pylons''' inscribed with phrases commemorating Eisenhower's life from birth through the Presidency.\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:EisenhowerCenterGrounds060708a.JPG|Grounds as seen from approach to place of meditation\nFile:Eisenhower House.jpg|Front of Eisenhower boyhood home, southwest corner\nFile:EisenhowerHome1.jpg|Southeast corner of boyhood home\nFile:Eisenhower Statue Abilene Kansas.jpg|Eisenhower statue in \"Champion of Peace\" circle, with memorial pylons in background\nFile:Defense.gov photo essay 100508-D-7203C-007.jpg|Inside Museum lobby; [[United States Secretary of Defense|Defense Secretary]] [[Robert M. Gates|Robert Gates]] and Army Capt. Josh Mantz, 2010\nFile:Defense.gov photo essay 100508-D-7203C-005.jpg|Museum tour; Secretary Gates and Museum Director Karl Weissenbach, 2010\nFile:Eisenhower Resting Place.jpg|View from entry corridor of \"Place of Meditation\"\nFile:DDEisenhowerGrave3.jpg|Graves of Dwight D. Eisenhower, Doud Dwight Eisenhower and Mamie Eisenhower\nFile:DDEisenhowerGrave2.jpg|Front view of graves\nFile:DDEisenhowerGrave.jpg|Grave of Dwight D. Eisenhower\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.eisenhower.archives.gov Official site of the Eisenhower Library, Museum and Boyhood Home]\n*[http://www.eisenhowerfoundation.net/ The Eisenhower Foundation (Kansas) website]\n*[http://www.c-span.org/video/?151630-1/life-portrait-dwight-d-eisenhower \"Life Portrait of Dwight D. Eisenhower\"], from [[C-SPAN]]'s ''[[American Presidents: Life Portraits]]'', broadcast from the Eisenhower Presidential Library, Museum and Boyhood Home, October 25, 1999\n\n{{US presidential libraries}}\n{{Dwight D. Eisenhower|state=expanded}}\n\n[[Category:Library buildings completed in 1962]]\n[[Category:Presidential libraries|Eisenhower, Dwight D.]]\n[[Category:Landmarks in Kansas]]\n[[Category:Dwight D. Eisenhower|Presidential Library]]\n[[Category:Museums in Dickinson County, Kansas]]\n[[Category:Biographical museums in Kansas]]\n[[Category:Presidential museums in the United States|Eisenhower, Dwight D.]]\n[[Category:Tombs of Presidents of the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dwight_D._Eisenhower_Presidential_Library,_Museum_and_Boyhood_Home"}
{"title_page": "Desert Garden Conservatory", "text_new": "[[File:Flowering Aloe in the desert garden.jpg|thumb|right|Entrance to the Desert Garden Conservatory]]\n[[Image:A CDP 4.JPG|thumb|right|Interior View of the Desert Garden Conservatory]]\n\nThe '''Desert Garden Conservatory''' is a large botanical [[greenhouse]] and part of the [[Huntington Library]], Art Collections and Botanical Gardens, in [[San Marino, California]].<ref>[http://www.huntington.org The Huntington Library website]</ref>   It was constructed in 1985. The Desert Garden Conservatory is adjacent to the {{convert|10|acre|m2|adj=on}} [[Huntington Desert Garden]] itself. The Garden houses one of the most important collections of [[cacti]] and other [[succulent]] plants in the world, including a large number of rare and [[endangered species]]. The {{convert|3000|sqft|m2|adj=on}} Desert Garden Conservatory serves The Huntington and public communities as a conservation facility, research resource and genetic diversity preserve. [[John N. Trager]] is the Desert Collection [[curator]].\n\nThere are an estimated 10,000 [[succulent]]s worldwide, about 1,500 of them classified as [[cacti]]. The Huntington Desert Garden Conservatory now contains more than 2,200 accessions, representing more than 43 plant families, 1,261 different [[species]] and [[subspecies]], and 246 [[genera]]. The plant collection contains examples from the world's major desert regions, including the southern United States, Argentina, Bolivia, Chile, Brazil, [[Canary Islands]], [[Madagascar]], [[Malawi]], Mexico and [[South Africa]]. The Desert Collection plays a critical role as a repository of [[biodiversity]], in addition to serving as an outreach and education center.\n\n== Propagation program to save rare and endangered plants ==\n\nSome studies estimate that as many as two-thirds of the world\u2019s flora and fauna may become extinct during the course of the 21st century, the result of global warming and encroaching development. Scientists alarmed by these prospects are working diligently to propagate plants outside their natural [[habitats]], in protected areas. Ex-situ cultivation, as this practice is known, can serve as a stopgap for plants that will otherwise be lost to the world as their habitats disappear. To this end, The Huntington has a program to protect and [[plant propagate]] endangered plant species, designated '''International Succulent Introductions''' (ISI).\n\nThe aim of the '''ISI program''' is to propagate and distribute new or rare succulents to collectors, nurseries and institutions to further research and appreciation of these remarkable plants. The ISI distributes as many as 40 new succulent varieties every year. Field-collected plants, [[cutting]]s or seeds are not sold, only [[seedling]]s, grafts and rooted cuttings produced under nursery conditions without detriment to wild populations.\n\n== The Schick hybrids ==\n\nThe '''Schick hybrids'''<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.huntington.org/BotanicalDiv/Schick/catalogindex.html |title=ISI Schick Hybrids |access-date=2008-05-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080515092628/http://www.huntington.org/BotanicalDiv/Schick/catalogindex.html |archive-date=2008-05-15 |url-status=dead }}</ref> are derived primarily from crosses of Harry Johnson\u2019s Paramount [[Hybrid (biology)|hybrid]]s, created in the 1930s and 40s, and from successive crosses of their progeny. Like the Paramount hybrids, the Schick hybrids can flower several times in a season and, with increasing age, can produce greater numbers of flowers. Under the Huntington\u2019s growing conditions the first flush of flowers is typically in April with successive flushes occurring in May, June and July, and, in some hybrids, even into August, September and October. These horticultural-significant [[cultivars]] are also available through The Huntington\u2019s '''ISI program'''.\n\n== Interior images of the Desert Garden Conservatory ==\n<gallery widths=\"180px\