Mad 29\"<br/>(Apocynaceae)</center>\nImage:P4300213-Uncarina-grandidie.jpg|<center>''[[Uncarina grandidieri]]''<br/>(Pedaliaceae)</center>\n</gallery>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Huntington Desert Garden]]\n* [[Greenhouse]]\n* [[Solar greenhouse (technical)]]\n* [[Seasonal thermal energy storage]] (STES)\n* [[cactus]]\n* [[cacti]]\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.cssainc.org/index.php Cactus and Succulent Society of America]\n\n{{coord|34.1272|N|118.1100|W|source:wikidata|display=title}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Botanical gardens in California|Huntington]]\n[[Category:Parks in Los Angeles County, California|Huntington]]\n[[Category:Huntington Library]]\n[[Category:Greenhouses in California]]\n[[Category:Cactus gardens]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Flowering Aloe in the desert garden.jpg|thumb|right|Entrance to the Desert Garden Conservatory]]\n[[Image:A CDP 4.JPG|thumb|right|Interior View of the Desert Garden Conservatory]]\n\nThe '''Desert Garden Conservatory''' is a large botanical [[greenhouse]] and part of the [[Huntington Library]], Art Collections and Botanical Gardens, in [[San Marino, California]].<ref>[http://www.huntington.org The Huntington Library website]</ref>   It was constructed in 1985. The Desert Garden Conservatory is adjacent to the {{convert|10|acre|m2|adj=on}} [[Huntington Desert Garden]] itself. The Garden houses one of the most important collections of [[cacti]] and other [[succulent]] plants in the world, including a large number of rare and [[endangered species]]. The {{convert|3000|sqft|m2|sing=on}} Desert Garden Conservatory serves The Huntington and public communities as a conservation facility, research resource and genetic diversity preserve. [[John N. Trager]] is the Desert Collection [[curator]].\n\nThere are an estimated 10,000 [[succulent]]s worldwide, about 1,500 of them classified as [[cacti]]. The Huntington Desert Garden Conservatory now contains more than 2,200 accessions, representing more than 43 plant families, 1,261 different [[species]] and [[subspecies]], and 246 [[genera]]. The plant collection contains examples from the world's major desert regions, including the southern United States, Argentina, Bolivia, Chile, Brazil, [[Canary Islands]], [[Madagascar]], [[Malawi]], Mexico and [[South Africa]]. The Desert Collection plays a critical role as a repository of [[biodiversity]], in addition to serving as an outreach and education center.\n\n== Propagation program to save rare and endangered plants ==\n\nSome studies estimate that as many as two-thirds of the world\u2019s flora and fauna may become extinct during the course of the 21st century, the result of global warming and encroaching development. Scientists alarmed by these prospects are working diligently to propagate plants outside their natural [[habitats]], in protected areas. Ex-situ cultivation, as this practice is known, can serve as a stopgap for plants that will otherwise be lost to the world as their habitats disappear. To this end, The Huntington has a program to protect and [[plant propagate]] endangered plant species, designated '''International Succulent Introductions''' (ISI).\n\nThe aim of the '''ISI program''' is to propagate and distribute new or rare succulents to collectors, nurseries and institutions to further research and appreciation of these remarkable plants. The ISI distributes as many as 40 new succulent varieties every year. Field-collected plants, [[cutting]]s or seeds are not sold, only [[seedling]]s, grafts and rooted cuttings produced under nursery conditions without detriment to wild populations.\n\n== The Schick hybrids ==\n\nThe '''Schick hybrids'''<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.huntington.org/BotanicalDiv/Schick/catalogindex.html |title=ISI Schick Hybrids |access-date=2008-05-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080515092628/http://www.huntington.org/BotanicalDiv/Schick/catalogindex.html |archive-date=2008-05-15 |url-status=dead }}</ref> are derived primarily from crosses of Harry Johnson\u2019s Paramount [[Hybrid (biology)|hybrid]]s, created in the 1930s and 40s, and from successive crosses of their progeny. Like the Paramount hybrids, the Schick hybrids can flower several times in a season and, with increasing age, can produce greater numbers of flowers. Under the Huntington\u2019s growing conditions the first flush of flowers is typically in April with successive flushes occurring in May, June and July, and, in some hybrids, even into August, September and October. These horticultural-significant [[cultivars]] are also available through The Huntington\u2019s '''ISI program'''.\n\n== Interior images of the Desert Garden Conservatory ==\n<gallery widths=\"180px\" heights=\"180px\" perrow=\"4\">\nImage:Desert Garden Conservatory interior.jpg|<center>The [[greenhouse]]</center>\nImage:Uncarina grandidieri PICT8748.JPG|<center>''[[Uncaria]] grandidieri''</center>\nImage:DGC-interior-echeverieas-be.jpg|<center>''[[Echeveria]]s''</center>\nImage:DGC-lithops-PICT4426.jpg|<center>''[[Lithops]]''</center>\n</gallery>\n\n== Plants in the Desert Garden Conservatory ==\n'''Cactaceae''' \n<gallery widths=\"180px\" heights=\"180px\" perrow=\"4\">\nImage:Astrophytum capricorne HBG 72527 PICT7627.jpg|<center>''[[Astrophytum capricorne]]''</center>\nImage:Echinocereus viereckii ssp. morricalii HBG 48099 Apr07.JPG|<center>''[[Echinocereus viereckii]] ssp. morricalii'' HBG 48099</center>\nImage:Mammillaria boolii HBG 48842 Oct PICT3673.jpg|<center>''[[Mammillaria boolii]]'' HBG 48842</center>\nImage:Mammillaria-fraileana HBG 59973 Jun PICT2757.jpg|<center>''[[Mammillaria fraileana]]'' HBG 59973</center>\nImage:Notocactus-herteri-HBG-7667.jpg|<center>''[[Notocactus herteri]]''</center>\nImage:Parodia leninghausii HBG 53682 May 07 PICT2773.jpg|<center>''[[Parodia leninghausii]]'' HBG 53682''</center>\n</gallery>\n\n===Other families represented===\n\n<gallery widths=\"180px\" heights=\"180px\" perrow=\"4\">\nImage:Lithops-marmorata-ssp.-marm.JPG|<center>''[[Lithops marmorata]]'' ssp. marmorata<br/>(Aizoaceae)</center>\nImage:PICT9018-Agave-attenuata-'E.jpg|<center>''[[Agave attenuata]]'' \"Emery Stripy\"<br/>(Agavaceae)</center>\nImage:PICT8942-Stapelia-leendertz.jpg|<center>''[[Stapelia leendertziaeex]]'' Scott Sykes<br/>   (Asclepiadaceae)</center>\nImage:Crassulaceae-'Pink-Pagoda'-.JPG|<center>''[[Crassulaceae]] \"Pink-Pagoda\"<br/>(Crassulaceae)</center>\nImage:Echeveria-secunda-PICT3408.JPG|<center>''[[Echeveria secunda]]''<br/>(Crassulaceae)</center>\nImage:Euphorbia handiensis 23311.JPG|<center>''[[Euphorbia handiensis]]''<br/>(Euphorbiacea)</center>\nImage:Adenium-multiflorum-63573-P.jpg|<center>''[[Adenium multiflorum]]'' x obesum \"Mad 29\"<br/>(Apocynaceae)</center>\nImage:P4300213-Uncarina-grandidie.jpg|<center>''[[Uncarina grandidieri]]''<br/>(Pedaliaceae)</center>\n</gallery>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Huntington Desert Garden]]\n* [[Greenhouse]]\n* [[Solar greenhouse (technical)]]\n* [[Seasonal thermal energy storage]] (STES)\n* [[cactus]]\n* [[cacti]]\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.cssainc.org/index.php Cactus and Succulent Society of America]\n\n{{coord|34.1272|N|118.1100|W|source:wikidata|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Botanical gardens in California|Huntington]]\n[[Category:Parks in Los Angeles County, California|Huntington]]\n[[Category:Huntington Library]]\n[[Category:Greenhouses in California]]\n[[Category:Cactus gardens]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Desert_Garden_Conservatory"}
{"title_page": "Danish Institute at Athens", "text_new": "The '''Danish Institute at Athens''' ({{lang-da|Det Danske Institut I Athen}}; {{lang-el|\u0399\u03bd\u03c3\u03c4\u03b9\u03c4\u03bf\u03cd\u03c4\u03bf \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u0394\u03b1\u03bd\u03af\u03b1\u03c2 \u03c3\u03c4\u03b7\u03bd \u0391\u03b8\u03ae\u03bd\u03b1}}) is one of the 17 [[List of Foreign Archaeological Institutes in Greece|foreign archaeological institutes]] operating in [[Athens]], [[Greece]].\n\nFounded in 1992, the Danish Institute focuses on archaeological research in Greece, but also operates as a cultural institute, with a programme of exhibitions and concerts. It is a contributor (with its [[Finnish Institute at Athens|Finnish]], [[Norwegian Institute at Athens|Norwegian]] and [[Swedish Institute at Athens|Swedish]] counterparts) to the [[Nordic Library at Athens]]. It is involved in archaeological fieldwork at Calydon and Kato Vassiliki ([[Aetolia]]), as well as [[Zea Harbour Project|Zea Harbour]] ([[Piraeus]], [[Athens]]).\n\n==Bibliography==\n*E. Korka et al. (eds.): Foreign Archaeological Schools in Greece, 160 Years, Athens, Hellenic Ministry of Culture, 2006, p.&nbsp;90-95.\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.diathens.gr/en Danish Institute website]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20180915161525/http://www.zeaharbourproject.dk/ Zea Harbour Project website]\n\n{{coord|37|58|16|N|23|43|50|E|source:google earth|display=title}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Foreign Archaeological Institutes in Greece]]\n\n\n{{Athens-stub}}\n", "text_old": "The '''Danish Institute at Athens''' ({{lang-da|Det Danske Institut I Athen}}; {{lang-el|\u0399\u03bd\u03c3\u03c4\u03b9\u03c4\u03bf\u03cd\u03c4\u03bf \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u0394\u03b1\u03bd\u03af\u03b1\u03c2 \u03c3\u03c4\u03b7\u03bd \u0391\u03b8\u03ae\u03bd\u03b1}}) is one of the 17 [[List of Foreign Archaeological Institutes in Greece|foreign archaeological institutes]] operating in [[Athens]], [[Greece]].\n\nFounded in 1992, the Danish Institute focuses on archaeological research in Greece, but also operates as a cultural institute, with a programme of exhibitions and concerts. It is a contributor (with its [[Finnish Institute at Athens|Finnish]], [[Norwegian Institute at Athens|Norwegian]] and [[Swedish Institute at Athens|Swedish]] counterparts) to the [[Nordic Library at Athens]]. It is involved in archaeological fieldwork at Calydon and Kato Vassiliki ([[Aetolia]]), as well as [[Zea Harbour Project|Zea Harbour]] ([[Piraeus]], [[Athens]]).\n\n==Bibliography==\n*E. Korka et al. (eds.): Foreign Archaeological Schools in Greece, 160 Years, Athens, Hellenic Ministry of Culture, 2006, p.&nbsp;90-95.\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.diathens.gr/en Danish Institute website]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20180915161525/http://www.zeaharbourproject.dk/ Zea Harbour Project website]\n\n{{coord|37|58|16|N|23|43|50|E|source:google earth|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Foreign Archaeological Institutes in Greece]]\n\n\n{{Athens-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Danish_Institute_at_Athens"}
